This simulation model uses the standard deviation of the population dataset multiplied by the effect size to produce the voltage that is added to each time point between 300 - 500 ms.

#Check is the packages are already installed and load the library
pkgTest <- function(...) {
  pkg <- list(...)
  for (i in 1:length(pkg)) {
    if (!require(pkg[[i]], character.only = TRUE)) {
      install.packages(pkg[[i]], dep = TRUE)
      if(!require(pkg[[i]], character.only = TRUE)) stop("Package not found")
    } 
  }
}

FUNCTIONS 1. The first function calculates the P3 amplitudes for the peak, mean, and adaptive mean amplitudes and combined the final data into a single dataframe. 2. The second function runs the P3 amplitude through ANOVA models. Calculating an ANOVA for each sample, sample size, and effect size, condition and method p-values are stored in a single dataframe for further analysis.

#Calculate the peak values for all three peak-picking methodologies
calculating_peaks <- function(data, peak_method = TRUE, mean_method = TRUE, adaptive_mean_method = TRUE){

        #Subsetting out the time window we expect the P3 to fall within
        data2 = data[(data$time >= 304 & data$time <= 504),]
        
        
        if (peak_method == TRUE) {
          
          #======================================================================================#
          #Generating peak and mean amplitudes
          #======================================================================================#
          #Calculating the peak amplitude
          peak_amps_erp = setDT(data2)[, .SD[which.max(PZ)], by = list(sample, 
                                                                       condition, 
                                                                       sample_size, 
                                                                       effect_size, 
                                                                       participant)]
          
          
          peak_amps_erp$method = "Peak Amplitude"
          
          peak_amps_erp = peak_amps_erp[, c(
          "sample",
          "condition",
          "sample_size",
          "effect_size",
          "PZ",
          "time",
          "method",
          "participant"
          )]
        }
        
        
        if (adaptive_mean_method == TRUE) {
          #======================================================================================#
          #Calculating the adaptive mean amplitude
          
          #This way seems to work if you want to use more than one index
          mean_amps_erp1 = rbind(setDT(data2)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 1)], by = list(sample,
            condition,
            sample_size,
            effect_size,
            participant)],
          setDT(data2)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 2)], by = list(sample,
            condition,
            sample_size,
            effect_size,
            participant)],
          setDT(data2)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 3)], by = list(sample,
            condition,
            sample_size,
            effect_size,
            participant)],
          setDT(data2)[, .SD[c(which.max(PZ) - 4)], by = list(sample,
            condition,
            sample_size,
            effect_size,
            participant)])
          
          
          mean_amps_erp = setDT(data2)[, .SD[c(
          which.max(PZ),
          which.max(PZ) + 1,
          which.max(PZ) + 2,
          which.max(PZ) + 3,
          which.max(PZ) + 4
          # which.max(PZ) + 5
          )],
          by = list(sample,
          condition,
          sample_size,
          effect_size,
          participant)]
          
          mean_amps_erp = na.omit(rbind(mean_amps_erp, mean_amps_erp1))
          
          
          mean_amps_erp = setDT(mean_amps_erp)[, mean(PZ), by = list(sample, condition, sample_size, effect_size, participant)]
          
          mean_amps_erp = mean_amps_erp %>% dplyr::rename(PZ = V1)
          
          mean_amps_erp$method = "Adaptive Mean Amplitude"
          
        }

        
        if (mean_method == TRUE) {
          #======================================================================================#
          #Calculating the mean amplitude
          mean2_amps_erp = aggregate(. ~ sample + condition + sample_size + effect_size + participant,
          data2,
          FUN = mean)
          
          
          mean2_amps_erp = na.omit(mean2_amps_erp)
          
          mean2_amps_erp$method = "Mean Amplitude"
          
          mean2_amps_erp = mean2_amps_erp[, c(
          "sample",
          "condition",
          "sample_size",
          "effect_size",
          "PZ",
          "time",
          "method",
          "participant"
          )]
          
          
        }
        
        
        #======================================================================================#
        #Combined all 3 datasets together
        #======================================================================================#
        # if (peak == TRUE & adaptive_mean == TRUE & mean == TRUE) {
          peak_methods = rbind.fill(peak_amps_erp, mean_amps_erp, mean2_amps_erp)
          return(peak_methods)
        # }
}





#======================================================================================#
#Combined all 3 datasets together
#======================================================================================#
simulation_analysis = function(files, path){
    
    
  #Load all of the data related to the file name sample
  data_stimulus_locked = paste0(
    path,
    files
    ) %>%
    map_df(~ fread(.))
  
  
  #Rename columns
  colnames(data_stimulus_locked) = c("PZ", "sample_size", "effect_size", "condition", "sample", "participant")
  
  #Need to add a time column
  data_stimulus_locked$time = rep(1:151, nrow(data_stimulus_locked)/151) * 4
  
  
  #CALCULATING P3 AMPLITUDES USING THE THREE PEAK-PICKING METHODOLOGIES
  peak_methods = calculating_peaks(data_stimulus_locked)
  
  
  #Calculating an ANOVA for each sample, sample size, and effect size. Store condition and method p-values for later analysis
  models <-
    plyr::ddply(peak_methods, c("sample", "sample_size", "effect_size"), function(df)
    c(anova(lm(
    PZ ~ condition * method, data = df
    ))$'Pr(>F)'[1],
    anova(lm(
    PZ ~ condition * method, data = df
    ))$'Pr(>F)'[2]))


  models = dplyr::rename(models, condition_pvalues = V1, method_pvalues = V2)

  all_models = rbind(all_models, models)
  
  return(all_models)
  
}
